<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="mocking-strategies">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>testing-developer</domain>
    <summary>Test doubles taxonomy and decision framework: when to mock, mock boundaries, partial vs full mocking, language-specific tools, and over-mocking detection.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>mocking</tag>
      <tag>test-doubles</tag>
      <tag>testing</tag>
      <tag>unittest-mock</tag>
      <tag>pytest-mock</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Mocking Strategies</title>
    <summary>Covers the five test-double types (Dummy/Stub/Spy/Mock/Fake), decision framework for what to mock (mock at boundaries, not internals), Python unittest.mock / pytest-mock, JavaScript vi.mock / Jest, Go interface-based mocking, time mocking, and external API levels. Includes an over-mock linter script.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Over-mocking is a silent suite killer: tests pass but production breaks because the mocked contract drifts from reality. Under-mocking makes tests slow and non-deterministic. The boundary-based decision tree and the autospec / over-mock-lint.py tools prevent both failure modes.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Deciding whether to mock a dependency or use a real one</item>
        <item>Writing Python mocks with unittest.mock / pytest-mock</item>
        <item>Writing JavaScript mocks with Vitest vi.mock or Jest</item>
        <item>Writing Go mocks via interface substitution or mockery</item>
        <item>Diagnosing "mock swallows typo" bugs (MagicMock, wrong patch target)</item>
        <item>Auditing a test suite for over-mocking</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>E2E tests where no mocking is desired — use e2e-testing</item>
        <item>Database isolation (use real DB with rollback) — use test-fixtures</item>
        <item>Fixture design decisions — use test-fixtures</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="five-test-double-types">
      <p>The five test-double types and their appropriate uses:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Dummy — passed but never used. Satisfies a required parameter. Example: null logger passed to a constructor.</item>
        <item>Stub — returns pre-configured responses to calls. No behavior verification. Example: always returns {status: 200} for an HTTP client.</item>
        <item>Spy — real object that records calls. Behavior is real, but calls can be inspected after. Example: spy on email service to check how many times it was called.</item>
        <item>Mock — pre-programmed with expectations. Fails the test if not called as expected. Example: assert payment.charge() called once with correct amount.</item>
        <item>Fake — working implementation with shortcuts. Example: in-memory repository instead of real database.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="selection-guide">
      <rule>Use Stub when you only care about the return value, not whether the dependency was called.</rule>
      <rule>Use Mock when you need to verify that a dependency was called with specific arguments.</rule>
      <rule>Use Fake for complex dependencies used heavily across a suite (e.g., a repository interface).</rule>
      <rule>Prefer Fake over Mock for stateful dependencies — Fakes are more maintainable long-term.</rule>
      <example type="good" title="Fake repository vs Mock repository">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Fake: implements the interface, simpler to maintain
class InMemoryUserRepository:
    def __init__(self):
        self._users = {}

    def save(self, user): self._users[user.id] = user
    def find_by_id(self, id): return self._users.get(id)

# Mock: heavy expectations, breaks when implementation changes
mock_repo = Mock()
mock_repo.save.return_value = None
mock_repo.find_by_id.return_value = User(id=1, email="a@example.com")
# Must assert every call — fragile
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="when-not-to-use-mocks">
      <rule>Do not mock the system under test itself — test real behavior.</rule>
      <rule>Do not mock value objects or simple data structures — use real ones.</rule>
      <rule>Do not mock what you do not own (third-party libraries) — wrap them in an adapter first, then mock the adapter.</rule>
    </section>
    <section name="mock-at-boundaries-principle">
      <rule>Mock at the architectural boundary, not inside the system under test.</rule>
      <rule>Boundaries: I/O (filesystem, network), time (datetime.now), randomness (uuid4), external services.</rule>
      <rule>Internal collaborators within your own codebase should use real implementations in unit tests.</rule>
      <example type="good" title="Mock the HTTP client boundary, not internal service logic">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Good: mock at the HTTP boundary
def test_payment_service_retries_on_timeout(mocker):
    mock_post = mocker.patch("myapp.adapters.stripe.requests.post")
    mock_post.side_effect = [Timeout(), Timeout(), Mock(status_code=200)]

    result = PaymentService().charge(amount=100)

    assert result.success is True
    assert mock_post.call_count == 3
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="partial-vs-full-mocking">
      <rule>Full mock: replace the entire object with Mock(). Use when you want to verify call patterns.</rule>
      <rule>Partial mock: patch one method on a real object with mocker.patch.object(). Use when most behavior should remain real.</rule>
      <example type="good" title="Partial mock: only patch the external call">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Partial mock: only patch the external call
def test_user_service_sends_welcome_email(mocker):
    mocker.patch.object(EmailClient, "send", return_value=True)
    service = UserService(email_client=EmailClient())
    service.register(email="new@example.com")
    EmailClient.send.assert_called_once()
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="time-mocking">
      <rule>Never test time-dependent code against real datetime.now() — use freezegun or mocker.patch.</rule>
      <example type="good" title="Time mocking with freezegun">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from freezegun import freeze_time

@freeze_time("2024-01-15 12:00:00")
def test_subscription_expires_after_30_days():
    sub = Subscription.create(start_date=datetime(2024, 1, 15))
    assert sub.expires_at == datetime(2024, 2, 14)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="mock-decision-tree">
      <rule>Ask: Does removing this dependency make the test faster or more reliable? If yes, mock it.</rule>
      <rule>Ask: Is this a third-party service that may be unavailable in CI? If yes, mock it.</rule>
      <rule>Ask: Is this a collaborator in my own codebase? If yes, prefer a real or fake implementation.</rule>
      <rule>Ask: Am I mocking to avoid writing a difficult test? If yes, fix the design instead.</rule>
    </section>
    <section name="python-unittest-mock">
      <rule>Use mocker.patch() (pytest-mock) inside tests instead of @patch decorator — cleaner scope management.</rule>
      <rule>Always use spec= or autospec=True to catch typos and attribute mismatches at call time.</rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>MagicMock without spec swallows typos silently</description>
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Bad: mock.notexistingmethod() returns a Mock instead of raising AttributeError
mock = MagicMock()
result = mock.notexistingmethod()  # no error — silent false positive

# Good: autospec raises AttributeError for methods not on the real class
mock = create_autospec(PaymentGateway)
result = mock.notexistingmethod()  # AttributeError caught immediately
        ]]></code>
        <reason>autospec validates call signatures against the real class at mock-creation time.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Patching at the wrong location</description>
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Bad: patches the original module, not where it's used
mocker.patch("stripe.Charge.create")

# Good: patch where the name is looked up (the importing module)
mocker.patch("myapp.services.payment.stripe.Charge.create")
        ]]></code>
        <reason>Python looks up names at call time in the namespace of the importing module.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="javascript-vitest-jest">
      <rule>Use vi.mock() / jest.mock() at the module level — hoisted above imports by the bundler.</rule>
      <rule>Use vi.spyOn() for partial mocking of a single method on a real object.</rule>
      <rule>Always call vi.clearAllMocks() or jest.clearAllMocks() in afterEach to prevent state leakage.</rule>
      <example type="good" title="Vitest mocking with sendEmail">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
import { vi, describe, it, expect, afterEach } from 'vitest';
import { sendEmail } from '../services/email';
import { registerUser } from '../services/user';

vi.mock('../services/email');

afterEach(() => vi.clearAllMocks());

it('sends welcome email on registration', async () => {
  await registerUser({ email: 'new@example.com' });
  expect(sendEmail).toHaveBeenCalledOnce();
  expect(sendEmail).toHaveBeenCalledWith(expect.objectContaining({
    to: 'new@example.com',
  }));
});
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="go-interface-based-mocking">
      <rule>Go mocking is interface substitution — define a minimal interface, implement it in tests.</rule>
      <rule>Use mockery for auto-generating mocks from interfaces; use manual mocks for simple cases.</rule>
      <example type="good" title="Go interface mocking with manual mock">
        <code lang="go"><![CDATA[
// Define the interface in production code
type Mailer interface {
    Send(to, subject, body string) error
}

// Manual test mock
type mockMailer struct {
    calls []string
    err   error
}

func (m *mockMailer) Send(to, subject, body string) error {
    m.calls = append(m.calls, to)
    return m.err
}

func TestUserService_Register(t *testing.T) {
    mailer := &mockMailer{}
    svc := NewUserService(mailer)
    svc.Register("user@example.com")
    if len(mailer.calls) != 1 || mailer.calls[0] != "user@example.com" {
        t.Errorf("expected one email to user@example.com, got %v", mailer.calls)
    }
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/over-mock-lint.py" purpose="Script to detect over-mocked test files in a Python project"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
